er work by other professionals and by lawyers in other countries. Part I of the book explores the literature on altruistic commitments among the public in general, and lawyers in particular. Part II traces the evolution of attorneys’ pro bono responsibilities. Part III presents findings of the empirical survey. Part IV draws on these findings, together with prior research, to propose strategies for increasing and improving lawyers’ pro bono activity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLAW / Legal Profession.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362507540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503625075423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503625075/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles